Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail post 20150528.3391146 reported on the development of _Rhodococcus rhodochrous_ as potential treatment for this disease. In fact, that post makes the statement: "This hopeful story may be an important 1st step in managing WNS. And its scientific backstory is just as fascinating."

Also this statement: "The bacterium does not cure WNS; it arrests the development of the fungus and inhibits its growth. But it is still a tremendous 1st step in finding ways to manage the disease."

So when I 1st read this story, I thought they had found a way to treat the bats without handling them all. This article does not address this, but is rather a limited update on the previous press release.

However, in bats that consume fruit, why not use the bacterium in/on the bananas and let the bats eat it? I am sure there are bats that will not eat it but if that is their 1st source of food, especially as they wake up weak, and it is close by, then it seems possible.

While that in itself seems like a daunting task, no doubt most bat habitats are mapped as researchers and foresters are keeping an eye on the bat population. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3792313,106.]
